# BISS Automation — Jenkins on OpenShift Setup Guide

Complete step-by-step guide to go from zero to a running
nightly pipeline on Red Hat OpenShift.

---

## Prerequisites

Install these tools on your local machine:

- `oc` CLI — OpenShift client
  https://docs.openshift.com/container-platform/4.14/cli_reference/openshift_cli/getting-started-cli.html

- `docker` or `podman` — for building/testing the image locally

Verify:
  oc version
  docker --version

---

## Step 1 — Log into OpenShift

  oc login https://YOUR_OPENSHIFT_CLUSTER_URL \
    --username=YOUR_USERNAME \
    --password=YOUR_PASSWORD

If your cluster uses token-based auth:
  oc login --token=YOUR_TOKEN --server=https://YOUR_CLUSTER_URL

---

## Step 2 — Create the OpenShift project

  oc new-project biss-automation

---

## Step 3 — Apply OpenShift resources

  oc apply -f openshift-jenkins.yaml    -n biss-automation
  oc apply -f openshift-pipeline-sa.yaml -n biss-automation

Verify everything is running:
  oc get pods -n biss-automation
  oc get routes -n biss-automation

Get the Jenkins URL:
  oc get route jenkins -n biss-automation -o jsonpath='{.spec.host}'

---

## Step 4 — Fill in DB credentials

BEFORE applying the secret, edit openshift-pipeline-sa.yaml
and replace all REPLACE_WITH_* placeholders with real values.

OR create the secret directly (safer — never in a file):

  oc create secret generic biss-db-credentials \
    --from-literal=db.url='jdbc:oracle:thin:@//your-host:1521/your-svc' \
    --from-literal=db.username='BISS_DATA_USER' \
    --from-literal=db.password='your_password' \
    --from-literal=db.inet.url='jdbc:oracle:thin:@//your-host:1521/your-svc' \
    --from-literal=db.inet.username='BISS_INET_USER' \
    --from-literal=db.inet.password='your_password' \
    -n biss-automation

---

## Step 5 — Add Jenkinsfile to your GitLab repo

Copy Jenkinsfile to the root of your BISS_Automation repo:
  cp Jenkinsfile /path/to/BISS_Automation/Jenkinsfile
  cp Dockerfile  /path/to/BISS_Automation/Dockerfile

Commit and push:
  git add Jenkinsfile Dockerfile
  git commit -m "Add Jenkins + Docker pipeline configuration"
  git push origin main

---

## Step 6 — Configure Jenkins

Open Jenkins in your browser (URL from Step 3).

### Install required plugins

Manage Jenkins → Plugins → Available → install:

  - Kubernetes Plugin         (runs pipeline pods in OpenShift)
  - Pipeline Plugin           (declarative Jenkinsfile support)
  - GitLab Plugin             (GitLab integration + webhooks)
  - Git Plugin                (checkout from GitLab)
  - JUnit Plugin              (publishes test results)
  - HTML Publisher Plugin     (publishes HTML report as artifact)
  - Credentials Plugin        (manages secrets)
  - Timestamper Plugin        (timestamps log lines)

### Configure Kubernetes cloud

Manage Jenkins → Clouds → New Cloud → Kubernetes

  Kubernetes URL:     https://kubernetes.default.svc
  Kubernetes Namespace: biss-automation
  Jenkins URL:        http://jenkins.biss-automation.svc:80
  Credentials:        (use the jenkins-sa service account token)

Click "Test Connection" — should show "Connected to Kubernetes"

---

## Step 7 — Add Jenkins Credentials

Manage Jenkins → Credentials → System → Global → Add Credential

Add the following (all as Secret Text unless noted):

  ID                      Type                  Value
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  gitlab-credentials      Username+Password     GitLab user + access token
  biss-db-url             Secret Text           BISS_DATA JDBC URL
  biss-db-username        Secret Text           BISS_DATA username
  biss-db-password        Secret Text           BISS_DATA password
  biss-db-inet-url        Secret Text           BISS_INET JDBC URL
  biss-db-inet-username   Secret Text           BISS_INET username
  biss-db-inet-password   Secret Text           BISS_INET password
  biss-email-password     Secret Text           Email SMTP password

---

## Step 8 — Create the Pipeline Job

New Item → Pipeline → name it "BISS-Automation-Regression"

Pipeline section:
  Definition:         Pipeline script from SCM
  SCM:                Git
  Repository URL:     https://rhosgitlab1.agriculture.gov.ie/automation/biss-automation.git
  Credentials:        gitlab-credentials
  Branch:             main
  Script Path:        Jenkinsfile

Save.

---

## Step 9 — Build the runner image (first time only)

The Jenkinsfile "Build Runner Image" stage calls oc start-build.
For the very first run, trigger this manually:

  oc start-build biss-automation \
    --from-dir=/path/to/BISS_Automation \
    --follow \
    -n biss-automation

Watch it build:
  oc logs -f bc/biss-automation -n biss-automation

Once complete:
  oc get imagestream biss-automation -n biss-automation

---

## Step 10 — Run the pipeline

In Jenkins, open "BISS-Automation-Regression" → Build with Parameters:

  ENVIRONMENT  : staging
  TAG_FILTER   : @regression
  HERD_YEAR    : 2026
  HERD_LIMIT   : 25
  SEND_EMAIL   : true (or false for first test run)

Click Build.

Watch the console output — you should see all 6 stages execute.

---

## Nightly Schedule

The pipeline is pre-configured to run at 22:00 Mon–Fri automatically
(defined in the Jenkinsfile triggers block):

  triggers { cron('H 22 * * 1-5') }

No additional configuration needed — it activates once the job is saved.
To change the schedule, edit the cron expression in Jenkinsfile.

---

## Reports Location

After each run, reports are available in Jenkins:

  Build → Test Results          (JUnit XML — pass/fail per TC)
  Build → Artifacts → html/     (HTML management dashboard)
  Build → Artifacts → docs/     (Word execution reports)
  Build → Artifacts → logs/     (Execution and failure logs)

